summary: As much as I enjoyed Killing Eve, some things just didn’t make sense. [[MORE]] Mainly when Bill decided to follow Villanelle in...
body:
As much as I enjoyed Killing Eve, some things just didn’t make sense. 

Mainly when Bill decided to follow Villanelle in a crowded nightclub even though she’s a professional assassin who literally poisoned a mark in close range like…did you really think about that? She’s an assassin. Why would you follow her into a dark, crowded night club? Not smart.

summary: The thing is, we better get some sort of confirmation that Eve's obsession with Villanelle is NOT platonic. Like, that's all we...
question: The thing is, we better get some sort of confirmation that Eve's obsession with Villanelle is NOT platonic. Like, that's all we need. They don't even have to kiss (although that would be fucking great). But they have to give us SOMETHING. We all know V is attracted to Eve, she's made that very clear, so we just need Eve to acknowledge her attraction as well and that would be enough.... I think lol
answer:
Well, luckily, I don’t think it’s a question of if Eve will acknowledge her attraction, it’s a question of when. The writers know better than to change something as fundamental as the whole plot of the books. Eve’s attraction is canon: you don’t just get yourself off next to your husband in bed while thinking about a psychopath and then claim ”oh I’m just a fan” (this still makes me grin so much, I’m awful). And before Paris, she sniffed the bloody coat! Come on, girl, seriously? Her expression when she did that was pure euphoria until… you know, four years of dust. (God, Sandra’s acting!)

It will probably take some time though, Eve getting there. Basically, in season 2, she needs to take a long hard look in the mirror and ask herself the following question:

title: The best TV of 2018
excerpt: It’s truer in 2018 than it was in 2017, or 2016, or 2015: Any survey of the year’s best TV can only provide a tiny sampling of the finest the medium had to offer. The perception of this particular year is that it was one characterized by good, not great programming—to which the TV critics of The A.V. Club offer, as a rejoinder, the number of worthy shows that aren’t on the list below. Please spare us the reminders of those we didn’t include; their ghosts and the second thoughts they conjure are already plenty haunting. Instead, revel in a year of television that introduced us to infatuated assassins and fatuous scions of wealth, expanded the worlds of its comedies to previously inconceivable bounds, and gave the best show of the decade the ending (and the musical coda) it deserved. And while you’re at it, give thanks to the reconciling sisters and bewildered military veterans who kept their dramatic exploits from running over the 30-minute mark. You’ll be grateful for that extra time when you’re still discovering all of 2018’s best TV (and the one effervescent period piece from 2017 that missed last year’s voting deadline—though it surely has a laugh-out-loud anecdote about why it missed that deadline at the ready) in 2019, 2020, and beyond.

summary:
One thing I really love about Killing Eve is that Eve is just as obsessed with 

Villanelle as 

Villanelle is obsessed with...
body: One thing I really love about Killing Eve is that Eve is just as obsessed with  Villanelle as  Villanelle is obsessed with her. I feel a lot of shows with the villain/hero obsession dynamic are very uncomfortable to watch because the villain is almost always way more invested in the hero than the hero is in the villain. For instance, I’ve only seen season 1 of Hannibal, but even with the tension between Hannibal/Will, I never wanted them together because Hannibal always had a lot more power in the dynamic than Will. Hannibal was obsessed with Will from the start while Will’s all “I don’t find you all that interesting.” In the serial killer/investigator genre it’s so common for the the villain to have to lure the hero into the obsession dynamic. Meanwhile, both Eve and Villanelle center their whole lives around each from the moment they notice each other. There’s no luring. Villanelle may be murderous and manipulative, but her interactions with Eve aren’t uncomfortable or predatory (outside of the fact that she’s…ya know. a murder.) They’re on equal footing from the beginning.  Villanelle isn’t going after Eve because she’s weak or easily manipulated, she isn’t trying to change her into a fellow killer. I mean, their relationship isn’t healthy by any means, but neither of them is taking advantage of the other. Which is really nice.

summary: I’m not sure if u heard but Jodie in a rlly recent interview just confirmed that there is quote “sexual chemistry” in season 2....
question: I’m not sure if u heard but Jodie in a rlly recent interview just confirmed that there is quote “sexual chemistry” in season 2. Do you think that means we are going to get some flirtation or a heated kiss or “devils tango” like that last anon ?
answer:
I DID NOT HEAR THIS. THANK YOU.

Okay. Okay. Now I am sooo hoping that we’re talking about the kind of slow burn that just makes you scream at the tv like:

In all seriousness though, if a huge amount of season 2 wasn’t Eve working out her own feelings for Villanelle, the fandom would riot. I think we’re going to get some more of this push-and-pull that’s been going on in season 1, and—oh lord—I wonder if the show will go as far as the book did, in other words: Eve got off thinking about Villanelle. Yeah, I’m still kind of blown away by that chapter…
